{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16229"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16229"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.03,0.51,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGynaecomastia is a benign enlargement of male breast tissue that occurs due to an imbalance between oestrogen and androgen effects (Image). The condition has distinct histological phases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the early histological changes in gynaecomastia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adipose tissue hyperplasia","Dense fibrous tissue formation","Ductal proliferation with stromal oedema","Glandular atrophy","Periductal calcification"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe early (florid) phase of gynaecomastia is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Eductal proliferation with stromal oedema\u003C/strong\u003E. This typically occurs within the first six months of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDense fibrous tissue formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of the intermediate phase, occurring after 6-12 months\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - While fat may be present, it is not a defining feature of early gynaecomastia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlandular atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in the late (quiescent) phase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriductal calcification\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a typical feature of gynaecomastia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these histological phases is important as they influence both the physical findings and treatment options. Early gynaecomastia is typically more tender and responds better to medical therapy than later phases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gynaecomastia progresses through three histological phases: florid (early), fibrous (intermediate), and quiescent (late)","The early florid phase is characterised by ductal proliferation and stromal oedema","The intermediate fibrous phase shows increased periductal fibrosis and stromal fibroblasts"],"references":["Johnson RE, Murad MH. Gynecomastia: pathophysiology, evaluation, and management. Mayo Clin Proc. 2009 Nov;84(11):1010-5. doi: 10.1016/S0025-6196(11)60671-X. PMID: 19880691; PMCID: PMC2770912","Cuhaci N, Polat SB, Evranos B, Ersoy R, Cakir B. Gynecomastia: Clinical evaluation and management. Indian J Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Mar;18(2):150-8. doi: 10.4103/2230-8210.129104. PMID: 24741509; PMCID: PMC3987263","Fagerlund A, Lewin R, Rufolo G, Elander A, Santanelli di Pompeo F, Selvaggi G. Gynecomastia: A systematic review. J Plast Surg Hand Surg. 2015;49(6):311-8. doi: 10.3109/2000656X.2015.1053398. Epub 2015 Jun 7. PMID: 26051284","Narula HS, Carlson HE. Gynaecomastia--pathophysiology, diagnosis and treatment. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2014 Nov;10(11):684-98. doi: 10.1038/nrendo.2014.139. Epub 2014 Aug 12. PMID: 25112235"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16229"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21291"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21291"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GTPTC3J0BHTJKiiRrJYXEwH9A1mVrE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GTPTC3J0BHTJKiiRrJYXEwH9A1mVrE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T20:59:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T20:59:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"